## Why This Is Asked
Designing runtime access control is critical for microservices in a ride-hailing platform. This tests integration of SPIFFE identities, policy as code (OPA), and Envoy ext_authz in a real-world, zero-trust setup.

## Key Concepts
- SPIFFE IDs and mTLS identity
- Open Policy Agent (Rego) for authz decisions
- Envoy ext_authz as a gatekeeper
- Service mesh zero-trust patterns
- CI test harness for policy validation

## Code Example
```javascript
// Minimal JavaScript test harness exercising OPA policy via REST API
const fetch = require('node-fetch');
async function test(spiffe_id, expected) {
  const input = { spiffe_id };
  const res = await fetch('http://opa.local/v1/data/authz/allow', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ input })
  });
  const json = await res.json();
  console.log(spiffe_id, json.result === expected);
}
(async () => { await test('spiffe://domain.org/finance/payment', true); await test('spiffe://domain.org/unknown', false); })();
```

